metadata.name: Encapsulated #11
metadata.description:
Have you ever felt fear? Have you ever felt tired? Have you ever felt trapped and watched? The bars of the big cities are supposed to bring us protection, but in the end, we are encapsulated in this big prison.

This project was made thinking about that feeling of prison ourselves and will participate in the #fxhashturnsone event. 

Fully made with p5.js and p5.grain

metadata.name: Verdant Brut #29
metadata.description:
Verdant translates to “lush, green” and Brut means “dry, raw, or unrefined.”

This series is less about impressions of nature, or vegetal growth… but rather the vibrant, lush world that abstract art can provide and while certain iterations may serve Brutalist aesthetics, it tries to focus on the unrefined/raw aspect of the definition with more fluid shapes that feel irregular and organic in a playful, almost adolescent way.

Palettes inspired by MOMO, Melissa Wiederrecht, Erik Swahn, Marcelo Soria-Rodríguez, Paul Klee, Mareva Millarc, Ernst Mether-Borgström, Douglas Herbert Courtenay Auburn, Jim Harris, Alayne Spafford, Man Ray, Lajos Kassak and William Lachance. While the palettes may not always reflect their trademark colors (if they even have any) they are an homage to individual pieces by the respective artists that have influenced this series in their own way.

4878 bytes of Vanilla JS with no libraries.

For more info on the chosen palettes and other inspirations, see article linked from the main project page: Regarding Verdant Brut

In live mode:
‘S’ : save as png (2376 × 3360)
’V’ : save as svg (without grain)

URL params in live mode:
‘g=n’ : no grain
‘g=p’ : paper grain
‘h=t’ : high resolution mode, 5940 × 8400 (Chrome only)

For example, if you wanted paper grain in high resolution, append “&g=p&h=t” to the url in live mode.

After rendering with these params, tapping 'P' will then save the png with those settings applied.

metadata.name: CHX-1 #70
metadata.description:
Glitching pixels like it’s 1999.

Inspired by 90’s digital aesthetics, CHX-1 takes a random selection of GAN seeds, combines them in unique ways, and processes them –individually and as a group– with a series of glitching dithering algorithms. Generating fun, original, colorful artworks. Millions of possibilities. Have fun!

<<< Base seeds generated offline using personal styleGAN2-ADA models. Image processing and combinations done generatively by the CHX-1 algorithm >>>

GAN –> p5js –> Blockchain


• Artworks can take a few seconds to load when running live code.

• Press “s” (when "open live" is active) to save a PNG image.

metadata.name: odium #58
metadata.description:
The idea behind "odium" is to mix the two previous works to create a new art, which maintains similarities with the previous projects, but also with its differences and peculiarities.

"odium" is based on an algorithm that I've been exploring since the "radium" and "illusions" projects. So this is the last of the series.

It is composed by with grainy/noise and flowfields, creating a glitch effect as it is finishing to render.
"odium" have random colormaps instead a configured palette system, patterns of growth and plays with randomized blendModes and colorModes, 
and I name it "odium"  because the form it grows and glitch reminds me how the hate sometimes slowly consume the mind.

This is a project made in p5.js


Omar Lobato, 04/29/2022.

metadata.name: Modern Times #155
metadata.description:
Created by Eko33, a generative artist featured at the Tezos Ecosystem Exhibition (Art Basel Miami 2021).

This generative artwork creates a limited series of distinctive artworks based on unique hash seeds.

The algorithmic approach of this collection generates a broad spectrum of unique outcomes, inspired by the "giant machine" from the movie "Modern Times."

Beyond a classic mechanical representation, Eko33 aims to convey multiple emotions while embracing the cold nature of algorithms.

Computer-generated generative art can be seen as a gigantic assembly line. Still, its true nature gives the artist complete freedom from all commercially available tools/constraints.

The collection "Modern Times" highlights the dark ages of generative arts using a bichromatic color palette and evolves toward the contemporary "Digital Renaissance" era using warmer, more acid and "pop" colors.

About Eko33:
Official fx(hash) page: https://www.fxhash.xyz/u/Eko33
Official Website: https://www.eko33.com/

metadata.name: Infinite Scaling System #123
metadata.description:
This generative system has a beginning, but no ending. It scales infinitely in different directions as unlimited shapes are added. Special care was taken to avoid memory overflows, impossibly big numbers, and poor performance. 

Rendered using P5.JS

metadata.name: aprendizajes #305
metadata.description:
aprendizajes is a generative art project that pays a tribute to the process of learning. 25% of primary proceeds go to Save The Children. Full description of the artwork+instructions here: https://www.iillucid.com/aprendizajes/

The artwork allows the user to:

* Change resolution: press 'd' followed by any number from 1 to 9 to add that amount to the pixel density. If you get a black screen you have surpassed what your graphics card can handle: press d + 0 to reset the pixel density. You can fine tune pressing d followed by + or - (+/- 0.5).
* Save image: press 's' to save the current image as png. For a higher resolution png, 1st increase the resolution using 'd' and then save the image with 's'.
* Tune image parameters: press 'z' (brightness), 'x' (contrast), 'g' (gamma), 'b' (blur) followed by + or - to adjust. Toggle tuning with 'a'. Press 'n' then + or - to adjust amount of noise.
* Redraw: 'r' (changes how lines are drawn)

It is recommended to read the full instructions on the article.

metadata.name: radium #20
metadata.description:
Simulating the idea  about if the human eye could get able to see the radiation frequencies.

"radium" is trying to bring the wondering of if its would be possible naturarely, how it would be if we see ultraviolet lights, radio waves and things like that, as some other earth creatures...

The variations is on some patterns that goes through looking like an the edge of a black hole, planet rings, and in some times even a landscape...

The soul of "radium" is the colormaps that are set to randomize the time its inserting new colors, the form of paint, intensity, the diffusion of grainy noise and the pattern of growth to simulate the frequencies emanation.
 A  sequential pulse growing or a rectroative pulse that grows  after it goes and came back in the opposite direction.




this is a work in p5.js

Omar Lobato Neto, 28/08/2022
Pompéu, Minas Gerais.
